<subSubSection id="51AB2228B8673FD8A37F250359F46915" pageId="12" pageNumber="133" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="3754202DB4E6EDA130ED353A01D55421" pageId="12" pageNumber="133">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="78DE04EB65F69BF0087287ECA50D6F9E" pageId="12" pageNumber="133">The specific epithet refers to the dense pubescent and villous indumentum.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="F4C3AD3C787CAD4B56C08CEC99D60537" pageId="12" pageNumber="133" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="78FE5B4C4E5B602627830D9EA84C9871" pageId="12" pageNumber="133">Distribution and ecology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="98F7CEE2C206D1D42BE3F86BEE3A656A" pageId="12" pageNumber="133">
<taxonomicName id="96B0C36AD1D47FE04E967148C15D2AE3" authorityName="X. X. Su" authorityYear="2019" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Tashiroea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Tashiroea villosa" order="Myrtales" pageId="12" pageNumber="133" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="villosa">
<emphasis id="1DE73F3737CDE851760C2C46931E4CF0" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="133">Tashiroea villosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is currently known from Pingnan, Jianou and Jianyang, northern Fujian, China (
<figureCitation id="0F8D64C89C5BD90BADAFFC7BC3C16056" captionStart="Figure 9" captionStartId="F9" captionText="Figure 9. Distribution of Tashiroea. Hollow triangles indicate the locations of Tashiroea villosa." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.127.36608.figure9" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/318131" pageId="12" pageNumber="133" tableDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.127.36608.figure9">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
). It often grows in grasses and bushes along streamside at elevations of 900-1400 m.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="91287EAF1DF2DD622AA036DDDE796637" lastPageId="13" lastPageNumber="134" pageId="12" pageNumber="133" type="notes">
<paragraph id="9C6D82C9E75332F37A63FEE54B9C499A" pageId="12" pageNumber="133">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="89DD1491D436CF86E62A061CBCFEAB23" lastPageId="13" lastPageNumber="134" pageId="12" pageNumber="133">
<taxonomicName id="0C567E142E386639627EA4B94B680BA7" authorityName="X. X. Su" authorityYear="2019" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Tashiroea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Tashiroea villosa" order="Myrtales" pageId="12" pageNumber="133" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="villosa">
<emphasis id="F7904935844653FDEA11D9F9E25EA50B" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="133">Tashiroea villosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is discovered by Mr. Xiang-xiu Su. He is an amateur collector in Fujian who had made an important contribution to the description of this new species. We therefore include him as the author of this name. 
<taxonomicName id="8AD9FA689A6D23A1EB6A171556732268" authorityName="X. X. Su" authorityYear="2019" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Tashiroea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Tashiroea villosa" order="Myrtales" pageId="12" pageNumber="133" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="villosa">
<emphasis id="B51511517172B933405C63F6DD20D54F" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="133">Tashiroea villosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<pageBreakToken id="7621C0F556FFEE9548812AAAC5DB0085" pageId="13" pageNumber="134" start="start">is</pageBreakToken>
the sole species currently known in 
<taxonomicName id="67DF36068AA0AB6FD596FEB1C02319F8" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Tashiroea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Tashiroea" order="Myrtales" pageId="13" pageNumber="134" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="AF032D7E9A0122F4657C8E99033627AE" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="134">Tashiroea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with densely puberulous and villous leaves (vs. glabrous) and smooth leaf surface sculpture (vs. furrowed). It is morphologically and phylogenetically closest to 
<taxonomicName id="4017F9701D4A50E188E5FF980BDC11F1" genus="T." lsidName="T. amoena" pageId="13" pageNumber="134" rank="species" species="amoena">
<emphasis id="DABED6FAF72D0AF114EC748E8B762D07" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="134">T. amoena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The two species are similar in height, leaf size and shape, inflorescence and stamen morphology. 
<taxonomicName id="6F8DCFDC26C694B5D331E155225C9429" authorityName="X. X. Su" authorityYear="2019" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Tashiroea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Tashiroea villosa" order="Myrtales" pageId="13" pageNumber="134" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="villosa">
<emphasis id="6DD909EF02121ADB6416893CB6594EDE" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="134">Tashiroea villosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is distinct from 
<taxonomicName id="5E52D926645B2B92748AFD3E71C0A10F" genus="T." lsidName="T. amoena" pageId="13" pageNumber="134" rank="species" species="amoena">
<emphasis id="5A831F5ADEDA2BF4BDC230A819AA7B05" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="134">T. amoena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the dense indumentum covering the whole plant (vs. petioles and inflorescences pubescent or sometimes glabrescent) and much larger bracts (9-19 
<normalizedToken id="334E95715693383022258C551A4BCA4B" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
5-8 mm vs. 1-2 
<normalizedToken id="417DB7664E3A7BA2E2CF239772611EA2" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
1 mm) in the florescence (
<figureCitation id="F6A19DC31352C0A927FC15C81293C931" captionStart="Figure 12" captionStartId="F12" captionText="Figure 12. Tashiroea villosa (A-B) and T. amoena (C-D). A Habit B Inflorescence showing large bracts C Habit D Inflorescence showing minute bracts. Photographed by Xiang-xiu Su (A, C) and Ying Liu (B, D)." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.127.36608.figure12" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/318134" pageId="13" pageNumber="134" tableDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.127.36608.figure12">Fig. 12</figureCitation>
). Geographically, 
<taxonomicName id="0F5064174892370E126F4727160C70B8" genus="T." lsidName="T. amoena" pageId="13" pageNumber="134" rank="species" species="amoena">
<emphasis id="E2035BB8089443B57CF27E2F5F5E2E5D" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="134">T. amoena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is widely distributed in southeastern China (Anhui, Fujian, Zhejiang, Jiangxi, Guangxi), whereas 
<taxonomicName id="226D9DFF1AB9EEC5C90324A2FFE910D4" genus="T." lsidName="T. villosa" pageId="13" pageNumber="134" rank="species" species="villosa">
<emphasis id="8A32633EE3E4D7B449873FB28C1F380F" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="134">T. villosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
occurs in northern Fujian where both species occur. Nevertheless, they have not been found to co-occur within the same habitat.
